---

<Layout
  title="How to Convert Your AbleCommerce Site Into A Mobile App"
  description="Learn how to convert your AbleCommerce site into a mobile app with MobiLoud - a powerful website to app service that lets you convert your existing setup into a true native app, with no rebuilding, no duplicate work required."
>
  <Nav />

  <section class="py-20 md:py-32 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <span class="text-sm font-semibold text-emerald-600 uppercase tracking-wider">Website Builders</span>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-4 mb-6">How to Convert Your AbleCommerce Site Into A Mobile App</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-slate-600 mb-8">Learn how to convert your AbleCommerce site into a mobile app with MobiLoud - a powerful website to app service that lets you convert your existing setup into a true native app, with no rebuilding, no duplicate work required.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-slate-50">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-lg prose-slate">
      <blockquote><strong>The Bottom Line:</strong> AbleCommerce doesn't offer any mobile app capabilities, and its .NET architecture means there's no ecosystem of third-party app builders to choose from. But there’s good news! MobiLoud turns your existing AbleCommerce storefront into a native iOS and Android app, with everything intact: your products, your checkout, your integrations, your customizations. No rebuilding required.</blockquote><p>You picked AbleCommerce for a reason. Maybe your team works in .NET. Maybe you wanted to own the software outright rather than rent it from a SaaS platform. Maybe you needed the flexibility to customize everything, host it your way, and run your business without paying transaction fees on every sale.</p><p>Whatever the reason, you've invested real time building out your store. Your product catalog, your AutoShip subscriptions, your QuickBooks integration, your checkout flow, the custom work your developer put into the ASP.NET codebase. It all works. Your customers use it every day.</p><p>Now you want a mobile app. And you've probably already discovered that AbleCommerce doesn't have one for you.</p><p>This guide covers your realistic options and the fastest way to get your AbleCommerce store into the App Store and Google Play without starting over.</p><h2>Can You Build a Mobile App With AbleCommerce?</h2><h3>AbleCommerce Has No Mobile App Features</h3><p>AbleCommerce does not offer any built-in mobile app capabilities. There's no app builder in the admin panel, no mobile app add-on to purchase, and no "generate an app" button.&nbsp;</p><p>The platform gives you a Bootstrap-responsive storefront that works well in mobile browsers, but that's where its mobile story ends.</p><p>This isn't a gap that's likely to be filled anytime soon. AbleCommerce is a mature, stable platform with a small team focused on maintaining core ecommerce functionality, compliance updates, and payment gateway integrations.&nbsp;</p><p>A native mobile app builder isn't on the roadmap.</p><h3>No Third-Party App Builder Ecosystem</h3><p>Platforms like Shopify and WooCommerce have large marketplaces with dozens of mobile app builder plugins. AbleCommerce doesn't have that.&nbsp;</p><p>Its .NET/ASP.NET MVC5 stack is fundamentally different from the PHP ecosystems where most third-party app tools have been built. The developer community around AbleCommerce is small and specialized. Nobody is building a drag-and-drop app builder for it.</p><p>So if you search for "AbleCommerce mobile app builder," you're not going to find one. That's not a reflection of the platform's quality. It's just the reality of a niche ecosystem.</p><h3>No Modern REST API for Custom Apps</h3><p>Here's the technical wrinkle that makes this even harder.&nbsp;</p><p>AbleCommerce's API is a .NET class library (CommerceBuilder), not a REST or GraphQL API that a mobile app could easily consume. It's designed for server-side development within the AbleCommerce codebase, not for powering a separate frontend application.</p><p>That means if you wanted to build a custom native app, you wouldn't just be building the app. You'd also need to build an API layer on top of AbleCommerce to serve data to it.&nbsp;</p><p>That's a significant engineering project - before you've even started designing screens.</p><p>A <a href="https://www.mobiloud.com/blog/progressive-web-apps">PWA (Progressive Web App)</a> is technically possible since your site already runs in a browser, but the "add to home screen" flow is clunky and unintuitive. Very few customers actually do it. And you still miss out on the App Store and Google Play as discovery channels.</p><h2>Your Options for Launching a Mobile App</h2><h3>Custom Native Development</h3><p>The conventional route: hire developers to build iOS and Android apps from scratch.&nbsp;</p><p>For an AbleCommerce store, this means first building a REST API wrapper around your CommerceBuilder backend, then building the mobile apps that consume it.&nbsp;</p><p>You'd need to recreate your product catalog views, your checkout flow, your subscription management, your account pages, and every other piece of your storefront in native code.</p><p>For a <a href="https://www.mobiloud.com/blog/how-much-does-it-cost-to-build-an-ecommerce-app">typical ecommerce app</a>, that's $150K-$300K for the initial build, depending on complexity. Then $50K-$100K per year to maintain, keep current with iOS and Android updates, and add features.&nbsp;</p><p>For a small-to-mid-size business running AbleCommerce, that math rarely works.</p><p>And even if the budget were there, the maintenance burden is real.&nbsp;</p><p>Your web store and your mobile app become two separate systems. When you update products, change pricing, add a new payment method, or adjust your checkout flow on the website, someone has to make those same changes in the app.&nbsp;</p><p>The most common outcome is that the app gradually falls behind the website until it's more liability than asset.</p><h3>Turn Your Existing Store Into a Native App</h3><p>There's a much simpler option.</p><p>Your AbleCommerce storefront already works on mobile. It's responsive, it handles the full shopping flow, and it includes all of your customizations and integrations.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.mobiloud.com/">MobiLoud</a> takes that working storefront and delivers it as a native iOS and Android app.</p><p>No API wrapper needed. No rebuilding your checkout. No recreating your product catalog in a separate codebase. Your website <em>is </em>the app. Update your store, and the app updates automatically.</p><p>The cost is a fraction of custom development. The timeline is weeks, not months. And your team doesn't need to learn Swift, Kotlin, or React Native.</p><figure class="w-richtext-figure-type-image w-richtext-align-fullwidth" style="max-width:1201px" data-rt-type="image" data-rt-align="fullwidth" data-rt-max-width="1201px"><div><img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63894f0e251e567f6e443bfa/6993ee2ac5423f79fb31c4d3_Mobi%20meta%20image.webp" loading="lazy" alt="__wf_reserved_inherit"></div></figure><h2>Why MobiLoud Is the Best Way for AbleCommerce Stores to Launch an App</h2><p>It's 100x more efficient than building a custom native app, yet the end result is essentially the same as what you'd get from a ground-up build.</p><h3>Everything You've Built Carries Over</h3><p>Your product catalog.&nbsp;</p><p>Your AutoShip subscription flows.</p><p>Your product kitting and bundling.</p><p>Your checkout with Stripe or PayPal or Square.</p><p>Your Avalara tax calculations.</p><p>Your QuickBooks sync.</p><p>Your custom ASP.NET pages.</p><p>&nbsp;Because the app runs your website, whatever works on your website works in the app - by default.</p><p>This matters especially for AbleCommerce stores because so much of what makes your store work is custom .NET code or tightly integrated third-party services. Rebuilding that for a native app would mean re-implementing business logic that took years to develop and refine.&nbsp;</p><p>With MobiLoud, you skip that entirely.</p><h3>Push Notifications Change the Game</h3><p>This is the single most important feature a mobile app gives you that a mobile website can't. Push notifications let you reach customers directly on their phone's home screen, with open rates that dwarf email and SMS.</p><p>For AbleCommerce merchants running AutoShip subscriptions, push notifications are especially valuable. Remind customers about upcoming shipments. Alert them when a subscription order ships. Notify them about new products that complement their recurring orders. Bring back customers who haven't visited in a while with a targeted offer.</p><p>You're already doing the hard work of building customer relationships. Push notifications make those relationships stickier.</p><h3>No Mobile Development Skills Required</h3><p>AbleCommerce merchants typically run lean teams. You might have a .NET developer who handles customizations, but you probably don't have iOS and Android developers on staff. MobiLoud doesn't require them.</p><p>MobiLoud is a fully managed service. The team handles the app build, App Store and Google Play submission, ongoing maintenance, OS update compatibility, and support.&nbsp;</p><p>Your developer keeps working on your AbleCommerce site in the .NET environment they already know. Everything they build on the web flows through to the app automatically.</p><h3>Your Store, Your App, Always in Sync</h3><p>When you add a new product on your AbleCommerce site, it's in the app.&nbsp;</p><p>When you run a holiday promotion, it's in the app.&nbsp;</p><p>When you update your shipping rates or add a new payment option, it's in the app.&nbsp;</p><p>There's no deployment cycle, no app update to push, no waiting for App Store review.</p><p>This is the operational advantage that matters most over time. Two separate systems always drift apart. One system that powers both your website and your app stays consistent by default.</p><h3>Built for B2B and Specialty Retail</h3><p>Many AbleCommerce stores serve B2B customers or operate in specialized verticals like industrial supply, outdoor equipment, and specialty retail. These businesses often have complex product configurations, customer-specific pricing, or custom order workflows.</p><p>A mobile app gives your B2B customers a faster way to reorder, check order status, and browse your catalog from a job site or warehouse floor. And because MobiLoud runs your full web experience, any B2B-specific functionality you've built into your AbleCommerce store is available in the app without additional development.</p><h2>How It Works</h2><ol><li><strong>Get a free preview.</strong> <a href="https://www.mobiloud.com/demo">Book a free consultation</a> and share your AbleCommerce store URL with us. We'll build an interactive preview so you can see exactly how your store looks and feels as a native app before committing to anything.</li><li><strong>App build.</strong> Once you're ready to move forward, the MobiLoud team builds your native iOS and Android apps. This includes push notifications, native navigation, your app icon, splash screen, deep linking, and any customizations needed for your store.</li><li><strong>Testing and QA.</strong> We test across iOS and Android devices. You test on your own devices and give feedback. We iterate until everything is right.</li><li><strong>App Store submission.</strong> MobiLoud handles the Apple App Store and Google Play submission process, including compliance requirements, screenshots, and metadata.</li><li><strong>Launch and ongoing support.</strong> Your app goes live. MobiLoud handles OS updates, App Store policy changes, maintenance, and support. You keep running your AbleCommerce store exactly as you have been.</li></ol><p>The typical timeline from first call to live apps is about four weeks.</p><h2>Next Steps</h2><p>MobiLoud is the single best way for AbleCommerce store owners to get a native mobile app.</p><p>Your store already works. It's responsive, it handles the full checkout flow, and it includes every customization and integration you've built over the years. There's no reason to rebuild any of that from scratch just to have an app.</p><p>The cost is less than 1% of what custom native development would run. The timeline is weeks. And every change you make to your website shows up in the app automatically.</p><p>Why spend six figures rebuilding what already works?</p><p><a href="https://www.mobiloud.com/demo">Book a free strategy call</a> to see how your AbleCommerce store looks as a native app. No commitment. We'll have a working preview ready for you to try on your own device.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FAQSidebar faqs={faqs} />
  <FinalCTA />
  <Footer />
</Layout>